Revival under a Great Leader
LONDON —— Two hundred years have passed since the Battle of Waterloo, where Napoleon's catastrophic defeat in that battle seriously damaged France's self-esteem to such an extent that General Charles de Gaulle omitted any mention of it in his writing on French military history.
Still, if "great" is a measure of personal qualities, both Napoleon and de Gaulle could be considered among the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would argue that there are no "great leaders."
For Marx, the class struggle in France produced an environment in which characters like Napoleon, described as "bizarre buffoons," could become heroes.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not an exceptional general, and his victories should be credited to the courage and dedication of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
No matter how great Napoleon may have been, we must determine whether it is appropriate to describe any leader as great.
If the answer is yes, then who can be described as great?
The political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believes that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
Firstly, can this leader recognize historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did it, as did his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; both, as Bismarck's memorable phrase has it, heard the "rustle of the divine cloak."
Second, did this leader make important decisions?
Naturally, if a leader is forced to make decisions, neither should they be held accountable nor lauded for them.
The key, therefore, lies in whether the leader had the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the right decision on behalf of the nation.
De Gaulle thus deserves a place on any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the post-WWII doldrums.
After regaining power in 1958, he again saved his country, suppressing two coup attempts, ending the Algerian War, and drafting the Fifth Republic constitution.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview, establishing their place in the post-war global order.
In fact, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in setting their countries' worldviews was perhaps too great.
Their successors continued for years to view the world—and their role in it—through a lens of constrained rationality and distorted decision-making.
As a result, the leaders of the two countries failed to achieve anything that could match the accomplishments of these two great leaders.
But one British prime minister can match them: she is Margaret Thatcher, a very controversial figure whom people either love or hate just as much.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was due to rebellious activities within her own cabinet and party.
It does not take universal popularity to be a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics cannot deny her impact.
Aside from being the UK's first female prime minister and almost certainly one of the earliest female prime ministers in the rest of the world, Thatcher helped to turn around Britain's economic decline.
Beyond that, her offensive against the powerful unions made the country more manageable at a time when it seemed to be sliding into turmoil and chaos.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be considered among the great leaders.
Similarly, while远非无懈可击 cannot be directly translated without context, Deng Xiaoping of China also has the qualifications to be considered a great leader.
Aside from helping Mao commit evil deeds, Deng played a decisive role in ordering the Tiananmen massacre in 1989.
But Deng simultaneously invigorated the market, leading China on a path of unprecedented development and prosperity that ultimately lifted hundreds of millions of Chinese out of poverty.
Many people hold Singapore’s founder and long-serving Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew in high regard, although he may have wished for a larger stage to showcase his talents.
In fact, the size of a country seems to have little bearing on one becoming a great leader.
I do not mean any slight when I say small countries like Luxembourg are unlikely to produce great leaders, especially given the relatively non-contentious political atmosphere there.
The United States, with its vast expanse, is a suitable place for great leaders to emerge.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — although not giants of thought — nonetheless showed remarkable judgment in establishing the postwar international order that would support peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed extraordinary talents — namely the art of rhetoric and the power to persuade.
John F. Kennedy had it all.
He accomplished a great feat: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
He has an unparalleled talent for inspiring people; indeed, his assassination only served to enhance the traditions he left behind.
In South Africa, no one can claim greatness since Nelson Mandela's death; Mandela embodied courage, authority, and majestic generosity.
In fact, he was the most charming and magnetic leader I have ever seen; the other two - former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former US Secretary of State Colin Powell - were either African or African-American.
And today?
The only one who can rightfully call herself great is the de facto leader of the European Union, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she is often underestimated at the start but rarely makes mistakes when it comes to making important decisions.
Like Helmut Kohl who set generous terms for German unification; Merkel stood up to Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and took a tolerant stance on the migration crisis.
I believe Marx and Tolstoy were wrong.
Political leaders – the wielders of political power – can change the situation for better or worse.
Merkel is the clearest example today, guiding Europe through the high-stakes survival crisis.
